{"award_age":52.0,"bio_image":"full\/cdfcea127e9c87b7b735467cbd26bedc023b9917.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"South Africa","date_of_birth":"1899-01-30T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1972-08-11T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/b\/b3\/Max_Theiler_nobel.jpg\/220px-Max_Theiler_nobel.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Max_Theiler","mini_bio":"<p><b>Max Theiler<\/b> (30 January 1899 \u2013 11 August 1972) was a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/South_African_American\" title=\"South African American\">South African-American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Virology\" title=\"Virology\">virologist<\/a> and doctor. He was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> in 1951 for developing a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Vaccine\" title=\"Vaccine\">vaccine<\/a> against <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Yellow_fever\" title=\"Yellow fever\">yellow fever<\/a> in 1937, becoming the first <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Africa\" title=\"Africa\">African<\/a>-born Nobel laureate.<\/p><p>Born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Pretoria\" title=\"Pretoria\">Pretoria<\/a>, Theiler was educated in South Africa through completion of his degree in medical school. He went to London for post-graduate work at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/St_Thomas%27s_Hospital_Medical_School\" title=\"St Thomas's Hospital Medical School\">St Thomas's Hospital Medical School<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/King%27s_College_London\" title=\"King's College London\">King's College London<\/a> and at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/London_School_of_Hygiene_and_Tropical_Medicine\" title=\"London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine\" class=\"mw-redirect\">London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine<\/a>, earning a 1922 diploma in tropical medicine and hygiene. That year he moved to the United States to do research at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Harvard_University\" title=\"Harvard University\">Harvard University<\/a> School of Tropical Medicine. He lived worked and lived in that nation the rest of his life. In 1930 he moved to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rockefeller_University\" title=\"Rockefeller University\">Rockefeller Institute<\/a> in New York, becoming director of the Virus Laboratory.<\/p>","name":"Max Theiler","place_of_birth":"Pretoria ,  South Africa","place_of_death":"New Haven, Connecticut","text":"Max Theiler , Physiology or Medicine, 1951","year":1951.0}